<div style="background: white; margin:1em; padding:10px 10px; border:1px immaterial #FCFCFC; border-radius: 3px; color: black;">
<center><span style="font-family: Bahnschrift; font-size: 24pt">'''The theory of the crystal-like shape of the universe'''</span></center>
<div style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13pt">
<div style="text-align: right">Blink University Professor<br>Tom Gimberson</div>
Recently, documents deciphering various [[Entity 70|Homo Callidus]] paintings in [[Level 1]] were transmitted to Base Blink. They depict a sparkling crystal with countless facets, as if made of glass. I was intrigued by this discovery and decided to delve deeper into the subject.

Therefore, it can be assumed that Homo Callidus had their own myths explaining the appearance of the universe to an outside observer: like a crystal with an infinite number of facets, which are superclusters of galaxies and levels; they called this crystal the Great One. Beyond the Great Crystal lies [[The Void|absolute emptiness]].

Our current concepts about the structure of the universe can be linked to the Great Crystal theory: just as a person can move between dimensions and levels using no-clip, so too can they move to another facet of the Crystal. In the [[The Frontrooms|Frontrooms]], this is explained by the hypothetical existence of wormholes, or mole holes.

In the view of Homo Callidus, the Great Crystal wraps around a ring-shaped formation of infinite scale called the Road, currently known as Level 590. They called the Road the entire life path of a person, which is completely different for everyone in the middle but the same at the beginning and end. That is, the highway in the endless sky is probably just a [[Phenomenon 9|tulpa]] that exists for the simple interpretation of the concept of the Road by our brain.

Based on rough interpretations of the drawings, we can say that Homo Callidus envisioned the creation of the world as follows: an immaterial intelligent being, which arose randomly (perhaps through quantum fluctuations) in the Void, created the spiritual world through the power of thought; thus, this being is the [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creator_deity creator deity], hereinafter referred to as the ''cosmic mind''.

It is unknown what happened after the tulpaefication of the cosmic mind's thoughts; most likely, it no longer participates in the development of the universe, which is similar to the concept of deism. In this case, the material world was created by a being that appeared in the spiritual world but acquired mass: Homo Callidus called it the Old Man, but its concept is similar to the Gnostic Demiurge. However, the Old Man cannot be called evil or good, because he can help people and sometimes destroy their lives. He can take any material form, but his favorite is that of an old man with a long beard.

This theory should not be taken seriously, as it is comparable to other ancient myths explaining the shape of the Earth, but the information presented above is interesting in that it proves the existence of certain religious beliefs among the earliest ancestors of humans.
</div></div>}}
